      <div xml:id="NA52-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaivaṉ celavu aḻuṅkiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what prevents HIM from going.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA52">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            mākkoṭi yatiraṟ pūvoṭu pātiri</l>
<l>            tūttakaṭ ṭetirmalar vēynta kūntaṉ</l>
<l>            maṇaṅkamaḻ nāṟṟa marīi yāmivaḷ</l>
<l>            cuṇaṅkaṇi yāka maṭaiya muyaṅki</l>
<l>            vīṅkuvark kavavi ṉīṅkal cellē </l>
<l>            nīyē</l>
<l>            yāḷviṉai ciṟappa veṇṇi nāḷum</l>
<l>            pirintuṟai vāḻkkai purintamai yalaiyē</l>
<l>            yaṉpilai vāḻiyeṉ ṉeñcē vempōr</l>
<l>            maḻavar perumakaṉ māvaḷ ḷōri</l>
<l>            kaivaḷa miyaiva tāyiṉu </l>
<l>            maitē kamma viyaintucey poruḷē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>We won't go to leave<note place="foot">Or <term xml:lang="ta">cel</term> in auxuliary function: "we cannot leave...".</note> the swelling salty<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uvar</term>: T.V.G.'s explanation is that this word can also mean 'sweetness', but this may simply be a question of perspective: physical or emotional.</note> embraces, embracing</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that we be joined with her beauty-spot-adorned bosom,</l>
<l rend="indent">joining together in the odorous fragrance of perfumes(?)<note place="foot">How to relate and interpret these three words connected with fragrance: <term xml:lang="ta">maṇam kamaḻ nāṟṟam</term>?</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">in [her] tresses covered with alternating blossoms, the pure plates</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the trumpet-flower tree with the flowers of the big wild</l>
<l rend="indent4">jasmine creeper.</l>
<l>You, considering manly work to be superior, daily,</l>
<l><choice>
<seg>you aren't content, desiring a living of lasting separation,</seg>
<seg>you [are] mad, desiring a living of lasting separation,</seg>
</choice></l>
<l>you [are] devoid of love, oh my heart.</l>
<l rend="indent3">Even if there were to enjoy the riches in the hand</l>
<l rend="indent3">of great generous Ōri, great son of warriors in hot battle,</l>
<l>light would be, you [just] go, the wealth to be made [and] enjoyed<note place="foot">Slightly puzzling is here the word order <term xml:lang="ta">iyaintu cey poruḷ</term>: one should rather think that wealth has to be made before it can be enjoyed.</note>.</l>
        </lg>
